                Harsco Corporation            








News about Harsco Corporation, including commentary and archival articles published in The New York Times.                    











Latest Articles






COMPANY NEWS

                    HARSCO SHARES IN STEEP DROP AFTER EARNINGS WARNING                
Shares of the Harsco Corporation, the steel-mill services company based in Camp Hill, Pa., plummeted 35 percent yesterday after it said that profits in the third and fourth quarters would not meet estimates as business slowed in Asia, Russia and South America. The company said after the markets closed that profit from continuing operations would be $2.35 a share for the year, 32 cents lower than analysts' estimate of $2.67. Harsco expects to report third-quarter results on Oct. 16. Its shares tumbled $12.9375, to $24.3125, in trading of 2.26 million, wiping out more than $590 million in market capitalization. Harsco's board authorized the repurchase of 2 million shares, in addition to the 400,000 shares remaining from previous buyback plans.










COMPANY NEWS

                    HARSCO TO BUY FABER PREST FOR $95 MILLION IN CASH                
The Harsco Corporation agreed yesterday to acquire Faber Prest P.L.C., which handles waste for the steel industry, for $95 million in cash as it continues to expand its international industrial businesses. Harsco, an industrial-services and manufacturing company in Camp Hill, Pa., said its Heckett Multiserv subsidiary would pay about $8.20 for each Faber Prest share. Harsco has announced two other acquisitions in the last three months: the Chemi-Trol Chemical Company for $46 million, to build its steel pressure tank business, and the EFI Corporation, a composite-cylinder business, for $7.23 million.











                    Military Contractor Sold to Buyout Firm                
The FMC Corporation and the Harsco Corporation said yesterday that they had agreed to sell United Defense L.P., a joint-venture manufacturer of tanks and other armored vehicles, to the Carlyle Group, a leveraged-buyout firm, in a transaction that seems to have as much to do with politics as economics. FMC and Harsco, which respectively own 60 percent and 40 percent of United Defense, accepted the Carlyle offer, worth $850 million, even though the companies reportedly received a higher bid worth $1 billion from the General Dynamics Corporation.










COMPANY NEWS

                    GENERAL DYNAMICS SAID TO HAVE HIGH UNITED DEFENSE BID                
The General Dynamics Corporation has reportedly bid $1 billion for United Defense L.P., an armored-vehicle business owned by the FMC Corporation and the Harsco Corporation. General Dynamics was the highest bidder, offering more than Carlyle Group in Washington, people familiar with the offers said. A final decision on the winning bidder has not been announced. The bids were disclosed yesterday in The Wall Street Journal. The acquisition would make General Dynamics the only United States armored-combat-vehicle maker and could face antitrust scrutiny. It is the only United States tank producer and one of two makers of Navy submarines and destroyers.











                    Company Briefs                
HARSCO CORP., Camp Hill, Pa., said it would merge its Sherwood brass-fittings division into the Taylor-Wharton Gas Equipment division to cut costs and add marketing channels for both businesses. The merged businesses would have more than $300 million a year in revenue.











                    Company Briefs                












                    Harsco to Acquire Symons                
The Harsco Corporation, an industrial products and services company, said today that it had agreed to acquire the Symons Corporation, a maker of concrete-forming equipment, in a stock transaction valued at about $27 million.











                    Executive Changes                
HARSCO CORP., Camp Hill, Pa., named Ronald W. Kaplan executive vice president of the company's Plant City steel division, effective Oct. 1, and president of the division effective Feb. 1, upon the retirement of the current president, Moore Tappan Jr. J. CREW INC., New York, appointed Gary Sheinbaum president of J. Crew Retail.










COMPANY NEWS

                    HARSCO HAS AGREED TO ACQUIRE MULTISERV OF LONDON                
The Harsco Corporation said yesterday that it had agreed to acquire Multiserv International of London for about $380 million. The acquisition will make Harsco the leading international provider of specialized steel mill services. Multiserv will be merged into Harsco's Heckett division, which provides services in metal reclamation and slag processing, recycling and environmental technologies. Multiserv operates in 21 nations and has annual revenue of about $350 million. Harsco's earnings this year may sustain a "minimal decrease" because of the acquisition, the company said. Harsco's stock rose 37.5 cents a share yesterday, to $38.75, on the New York Stock Exchange.











                    2 Military Contractors Plan A Joint Venture on Vehicles                
In the latest sign of retrenchment among military contractors, the FMC Corporation and the Harsco Corporation, two leading manufacturers of military vehicles, said they had reached a preliminary agreement to combine those operations in a joint venture to be controlled by FMC. The two companies estimated that the venture would have sales of $1.2 billion next year. It would be 60 percent owned by FMC, a mining, machinery and chemicals conglomerate that has its corporate headquarters here. FMC's military systems group, based in Santa Clara, Calif., is by far the larger of the two operations, but its orders have been dropping. Makes Bradley Fighting Vehicle "Neither one of us wanted to commit significant new investment to the industry," said Robert N. Burt, chairman, chief executive and president of FMC, when asked about the decision to pool interests instead of arranging for one company to sell its business to the other. Mr. Burt said FMC expected Army spending on tracked and armed vehicles, the company's most important market segment, to decline from $4 billion a year ago to about $1 billion by 1995.














COMPANY NEWS

                    Harsco Order Increased by $247 Million                
The Harsco Corporation said yesterday that it had received a $247 million expanded order for five-ton trucks destined for Saudi Arabia. The order, for 2,486 trucks, came about when the Saudi Government exercised an option for more vehicles under an original order placed in February for 2,633 trucks. It was the second option exercised by the Saudis under the original contract; in May, they called for 781 more trucks.










COMPANY NEWS

                    Carlyle Raises Stake in Harsco                
LEAD: The Carlyle Group, the Washington-based merchant bank, has raised its stake in the Harsco Corporation to 8.47 percent from 7.25 percent. In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, Carlyle also said it continued to hold discussions with financial sources and possible partners about ''increasing its investment in Harsco through a possible business combination transaction.










COMPANY NEWS

                    Carlyle Discloses 6.27% Harsco Stake                
LEAD: The Carlyle Group L.P., a Washington investment firm, said that it had acquired 6.27 percent of the Harsco Corporation and that it believed the pipe-fitting and metals concern, based in Camp Hill, Pa., was ''a potentially attractive acquisition candidate.''











                    Harsco Gets Deal Worth $1 Billion                
The Harsco Corporation, a contractor for combat and tactical vehicles for the Army, said that it had been awarded a five-year contract worth about $1 billion to make 15,218 tactical trucks for the Army.










BUSINESS PEOPLE

                    Executive Is Named To 2 Posts at Harsco                
The Harsco Corporation, a metals fabricator that also makes military combat vehicles, has named Malcolm W. Gambill, an engineer who headed its metals reclamation division for nine years, president and chief operating officer. Mr. Gambill, 54, who has been executive vice president since October, succeeds Fred J. Mattscheck, 62, who retired but will remain a director. Jeffrey J. Burdge, 62, remains chairman and chief executive of the company, which is based in Camp Hill, Pa., near Harrisburg.











                    Harsco Corp. Elects                












                    Harsco Corporation Picks High Executive                
The Harsco Corporation, a Harrisburg, Pa., metals refiner, announced yesterday the election of J.G. Underwood as an executive vice president.











                    Nixon joins the Board Of Harsco Corporation                












                    C.B.S. ACQUIRES GUITAR CONCERN; Purchases Fender Co. for $13 Million in Cash Deal                
The Columbia Broadcasting System, Inc., which entered the sports field by acquiring the New York Yankees, is further diversifying into the guitar and amplifier manufacturing business.











                    Director Named by Harsco                











